value.0: Elrienia is a long-time caretaker of the Shrine of Eilistraee. She goes about her duties as High Priestess with a calm, welcoming smile.

Value.value: *she smiles warmly* Welcome to the Shrine of Eilistraee.
There's food by the campfire just to the northeast, if you're hungry. *she points*

Guardians of the Shrine of Eilistraee, these drow are capable warriors.

Fiercely sought after by certain trackers and wardens, these helms possess horn-shaped ear cones that amplify the wearer's hearing tenfold. While the materials used in creation offer little in terms of protection to the face, it offers an unrivaled advantage when it comes to aural detection.

It’s a well known fact that elves are foppish gits, barely able to lift their own swords without a limp-wristed floppy motion. It was for this very reason that these boots were forged. 

The master elven smith Yal’driirmathileh Mastiiramaeviil, spent many long hours making these boots for the elven protectors of the long forgotten court of Myth Drannor. When the kingdom fell, many of these boots were lost, some fell into the hands of those responsible for the fall, others are a prized possession from a dragons hoard. 

Perhaps the adventurer who has stumbled upon them now will use them to serve their intended purpose. Perhaps though, they have simply made another step along the road to obscurity.
A polished golden shield set with a large gemstone that seems to act as a third eye for the shield holder, allowing them to see more than most with a conventional tower shield.
The tower shield is a veritable wall of protection, though it can be quite cumbersome to carry on an adventure.

The magically enhanced drow piwafi cloak is one of the most important accoutrements of a drow's possession. Even the most common of these cloaks carries a most powerful enchantment to protect its wearer. All drow long to own a piwafi; though, only those who have proven themselves useful, or who come from rich, powerful families can afford to own one.

Crafted with care by the reclusive and little known sea-elves, these rings are a simple silver band wrought in a somewhat waving pattern, clasping two twin blue pearls. Each pearl is enchanted to help the wearer hear and see in the depths of the murky ocean, as well as the ring itself providing some minor magical fortification.
A copy of an amulet identifying one as Sutrinos, an elite leader of the Melee-Magthere.  These amulets are only worn by commanders that have proven their worth time and time again to the academy.

Captain Eareng is an intimidating drow, but clearly cares deeply for the shrine and its people. For the moonstone Templar, she demands the best, and gives her all.

Iron plated greaves forged for the most determined of dwarven warriors with the Dark Spire. Their warriors would wear these heavily enchanted pieces of armor, and become near unbeatable. Unfortunately, all but a small few of these were lost when the giants of fire and ice overtook the mountain.

Regardless of the defeat of the dwarves long ago, these boots still retain their durability and ability to retain a blow, just as their previous owners.

All seemed lost the dark day that the island Zanshibon was absorbed into the abyss. Many lamented the great evil that had happened. One however who had once called the island home and had been selling his wares when it was lost found new focus and drive as a craftsman. They say he forged many shields and sets of armor so the agents of the abyss could be made to pay. His last shield made days before his death, his last defence is potent piece of protection indeed.

Much of the north was once the domain of giants and trolls. It is said when the first men came to the Ostland, Cariagh and Wiltun regions that all was ruled by Grundisvarg the witch queen of trolls. Each of the locals islands claims one of its heroes slew her and while none can prove who did so powerful rune carved troll bone rings are often found that claim were crafted from the troll queen's bones.

Elemental Defence items confer partial resistance to all common forms of elemental damage and increase the user's defence.

Helms such as these have only recently begun to surface in the region, however they look ancient. Relics of an old war, long forgotten and a time nearly lost, these powerful artifacts were likely worn by the champions or paragons of the people that created them.

While the original creators of these helms seem to remain unknown, they do bare an uncanny resemblance to the natives of the Mylock Hills.

A glimmering silver bastard sword that rests at the base of the statue of the Dark Maiden.  At night, when the moon is directly overhead, this weapon seems to shine with a faint glow.

Be always kind, except in battle with evil. Encourage happiness everywhere. Learn and teach new songs, dances, and the flowing dance of skilled swordwork. Promote harmony between the races. Befriend strangers, shelter those without homes, and feed the hungry. Repay rudeness with kindness. Repay violence with swift violence so that those who cause it are quickly dealt with. Aid drow in distress and give them the Lady's message: "A rightful place awaits you in the Realms Above, in the Land of the Great Light. Come in peace and live beneath the sun again where trees and flowers grow."

An elf-sized statue of Eilistraee, the Dark Maiden. It is carved from obsidian, with blue-white moonstones for the eyes. Recently repaired, its hands are poised in a way that it looks like it may have once held the silver bastard sword that now lies at the base of the statue.

Carved into the surface of this marker in Common, Elven, and Dark Elven, this sign bears the legend:

"Welcome to the Shrine of Eilistraee, travellers. We ask only that you leave your prejudices and violence here before you enter. All whom can are welcome to rest here, for however long is wished."

The black stone of this tablet bares a list of names, dates of birth and cause of death, all listed here are friends, family, loved ones and residents of the Shrine of Eilistraee. The fact most died young is a mute and sorrowful testament to the cost of the war between Eilistraees faithful and the forces of evil.

This basin can be used to remove or replace the Moon Path. Provided one knows how, of course.

The Moon Path is a solid bridge made of pure, pale moonlight. It is a glowing white translucent force like a glass strip which will carry you without fail to the other side. Unlike glass, though, it will not break or crack beneath your weight.
